    how to activate venv

    youâ€™re asking about activating a virtual environment (venv) in Python, not env variables. Letâ€™s go step by step:

ğŸ”¹ 1. Create a Virtual Environment

From your project root, run:

python -m venv venv


This creates a folder named venv that contains your isolated Python environment.

ğŸ”¹ 2. Activate the Virtual Environment
âœ… On Windows (Command Prompt)
venv\Scripts\activate

âœ… On Windows (PowerShell)
.\venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1

âœ… On Mac/Linux
source venv/bin/activate

ğŸ”¹ 3. How do you know itâ€™s activated?

Your terminal prompt will show (venv) at the beginning.

Example:

(venv) C:\Users\you\project>

ğŸ”¹ 4. Deactivate

To exit the virtual environment:

deactivate


âš¡ Now, any packages you install with pip install ... will stay inside this venv instead of affecting your global Python.